The paper deals with the noise complexity of differentially private mechanisms in the setting of linear queries, which involves concepts from information theory (cs.IT), data structures (cs.DS), and machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also discusses the geometry of the set of queries, which is a topic in computational geometry (cs.CG) and theoretical computer science (cs.CC). Finally, the paper considers the security implications of differential privacy, which falls under the category of cryptography (cs.CR).
